Data Protection Addendum
Last Updated:
January 8, 2025
General Terms
This Data Protection Addendum (comprising these General Terms and the Jurisdiction-Specific Terms) (“
DPA
”) supplements, is in addition to, and is hereby incorporated into the Agreement between Company and Meta (individually, each is a “
Party
” and, collectively, “
Parties
”). This DPA does not limit Company’s obligations or Meta’s rights under the Agreement.
Applicability
1.1
General Terms.
Company’s performance under the Agreement and Company's Processing of Personal Data under the Agreement shall be in compliance with these General Terms and all Data Protection Requirements applicable to such performance or Processing.
1.2
Jurisdiction-Specific Terms.
Without limiting the foregoing, Company shall also comply with the following jurisdiction-specific terms, to the extent such terms are applicable (each, a “
Jurisdiction-Specific Term
” and, collectively, the “
Jurisdiction-Specific Terms
”):
If European Data Protection Requirements apply to the Meta Platforms Data Processed by Company or Personal Data shared by Company with Meta (as applicable) under the Agreement, then the terms available at
https://www.facebook.com/legal/terms/Privacy/Europe/
(the “
European Region Terms
”) (incorporated into this DPA by this reference) shall apply to such data.
If USA Data Protection Requirements apply to the Meta Platforms Data Processed by Company or Personal Data shared by Company with Meta (as applicable) under the Agreement, then the terms available at
https://www.facebook.com/legal/terms/Privacy/USA/
(the “
USA Terms
”) (incorporated into this DPA by this reference) shall apply to such data.
If LATAM, AMET, and Canadian Data Protection Requirements apply to the Meta Platforms Data Processed by Company or Personal Data shared by Company with Meta (as applicable) under the Agreement, then the terms available at
https://www.facebook.com/legal/terms/Privacy/LATAM-AMET-CANADA/
(the “
LATAM, AMET, and Canadian Terms
”) (incorporated into this DPA by this reference) shall apply to such data.
If APAC Data Protection Requirements apply to the Meta Platforms Data Processed by Company or Personal Data shared  by Company with Meta (as applicable) under the Agreement, then the terms available at
https://www.facebook.com/legal/terms/Privacy/APAC/
(the “
APAC Terms
”) (incorporated into this DPA by this reference) shall apply to such data.
1.3
Conflicts.
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in the Agreement, to the extent there is a conflict or inconsistency between the Agreement, the General Terms, and any Jurisdiction-Specific Terms, the following order of precedence shall apply to determine the term(s) that govern (unless such term(s) contradict a requirement under Applicable Law in which case such requirement shall prevail): (i) the Jurisdiction-Specific Terms; (ii) the General Terms; and (iii) the Agreement. If Meta has entered into a business associate agreement for employee benefits administration or other purposes with Company, the business associate agreement and not this DPA shall govern the Processing of Protected Health Information, as such term is defined by the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996, as amended (collectively, “
HIPAA
”), and this DPA otherwise shall still apply to Company’s performance under the Agreement and Company's Processing of all other Personal Data which is not Protected Health Information under the Agreement.
1.4
Company's Status
Company shall be deemed to be a "Service Provider" and "Processor" under this DPA, save to the extent where Company is identified only as a "Third Party" or "Controller" in the Agreement.
Data Protection Terms
2.1.
General Safeguards.
Meta may retain or disclose documentation and information regarding Processing under the Agreement as Meta deems reasonably necessary to comply or demonstrate compliance with Applicable Law.
Company shall reasonably cooperate with Meta’s reasonable periodic requests for information regarding Company’s privacy and security practices and compliance with this DPA, including information Meta deems reasonably necessary to comply or demonstrate compliance with Applicable Law.
2.2.
Service Provider.
To the extent Company is a “Service Provider” or “Processor” (as identified pursuant to Section 1.4):
If Meta determines in its reasonable discretion that Company has violated this DPA, then Meta may take enforcement action against Company by limiting, suspending, or terminating Company’s access to Meta Platforms Data or taking other action that may be reasonably necessary to protect the privacy or security of Meta Platforms Data. Such action will not limit any of Meta’s other rights or remedies at law or in equity.
Company shall Process Meta Platforms Data solely for and at the direction of Meta, for the purposes specified in the Agreement (including this DPA) and for no other individual or entity and for no other purpose, except as permitted by the Jurisdiction-Specific Terms or as necessary to comply with Applicable Law (upon Meta’s request, Company will provide Meta with information regarding such Processing to the extent permitted under Applicable Law).
Company shall not disclose Meta Platforms Data, except for and at the direction of Meta for the purposes specified in the Agreement (including this DPA) and for no other purpose, except as permitted by the Jurisdiction-Specific Terms or as necessary to comply with Applicable Law (upon Meta’s request, Company shall provide Meta with information regarding such disclosure to the extent permitted under Applicable Law).
Company shall ensure that all persons authorized to Process Meta Platforms Data on behalf of Company in accordance with the Agreement (including this DPA) have committed themselves in writing to confidentiality or are under an appropriate statutory obligation of confidentiality in relation to such Meta Platforms Data.
Taking into account the nature of the Processing, Company shall assist Meta by implementing and maintaining appropriate technical, physical and organizational measures with respect to Meta Platforms Data, insofar as this is possible, to enable Meta to fulfill its obligations to respond to requests for the exercise of Privacy Rights.
If and to the extent Company is permitted under the Agreement to use a Subprocessor, Company shall ensure that each Subprocessor’s Processing (including disclosure) of Meta Platforms Data is consistent with the Agreement (including this DPA). Company acknowledges and agrees that Company shall remain fully liable to Meta for any acts or omissions of its Subprocessors.
Unless required by Applicable Law, Company shall not notify or make any statement (or provide any documents) to any third party (including the media, relevant regulators, supervisory authorities and individuals) about matters concerning any Processing of Meta Platforms Data (including regarding any Data Incident), without the prior written approval of Meta. Where Company is required by Applicable Law to notify or make a statement (or provide any documents) to any third party in the absence of approval from Meta, Company shall promptly provide to Meta a copy of any such notification, statements or documents unless prohibited by Applicable Law. Nothing in this Section 2.2(g) shall prevent Company from seeking legal advice from third parties in relation to Company’s compliance with Applicable Law, provided that Company shall comply with its confidentiality obligations owed to Meta.
Except as may otherwise be required by Applicable Law, at the choice of Meta, Company shall promptly delete or return to Meta (and procure that its Subprocessors promptly delete or return to Meta) all Meta Platforms Data upon completion of the Services (if applicable) or the termination of the Agreement, whichever is earlier, or upon Meta’s request. Company shall demonstrate to the reasonable satisfaction of Meta that it has taken such measures. Where Applicable Law prevents Company from returning or deleting all or part of the Meta Platforms Data, Company shall at all times preserve the confidentiality of such Meta Platforms Data retained by it and shall only actively Process such Meta Platforms Data after such date in order to comply with the Applicable Law to which it is subject.
2.3.
Third Party.
To the extent Company is a “Third Party” or “Controller” (as identified pursuant to Section 1.4) and Company receives or Processes Meta Platforms Data:
If Meta determines in its reasonable discretion that Company has violated the Meta Terms, then Meta may take enforcement action against Company by limiting, suspending, or terminating Company’s access to Meta Platforms Data or taking other action that may be reasonably necessary to protect the privacy or security of Meta Platforms Data. Such action will not limit any of Meta’s other rights or remedies at law or in equity.
If requested by Meta (no more than once annually in the ordinary course), Company shall certify to Meta its purpose(s) or use(s) for Meta Platforms Data, that each such purpose or use complies with the Meta Terms, and that it is otherwise in compliance with the Meta Terms.
Meta may conduct, and Company shall promptly cooperate with, regular monitoring of Company’s compliance with the Meta Terms and its Processing of Meta Platforms Data.
If either Party receives any correspondence, inquiry, or complaint from any individual (including to exercise any Privacy Rights concerning Meta Platforms Data), supervisory authority, other relevant regulator, or other third party in connection with Meta Platforms Data Processed by Company (collectively, “
Correspondence
”), then the Parties shall cooperate in good faith as necessary to enable that Party to respond to such Correspondence and fulfill their respective obligations under Data Protection Requirements.
Security Terms Regarding Meta Platforms Data
3.1
Information Security.
To the extent Company receives or Processes Meta Platforms Data:
In addition to any other data security terms set forth in the Agreement, Company’s safeguards for Meta Platforms Data will include Company maintaining an information security and privacy program that: (i) is designed to protect the security, and protect against the unauthorized or unlawful Processing, of Meta Platforms Data; (ii) meets the applicable standards of industry practice that are relevant to Company’s activities and the volume and sensitivity of Meta Platforms Data, including the appropriate physical, technical and organizational measures that protect against the unauthorized or unlawful Processing of Meta Platforms Data; (iii) includes an appropriate network security program; and (iv) complies with Data Protection Requirements applicable to Meta Platforms Data or the Processing thereof.
Upon Meta's reasonable request, Company shall participate in initial and periodic third-party assessments to address privacy and security requirements with respect to Company's Processing of Meta Platforms Data under the Agreement.
Company shall not request, on Meta’s behalf, user passwords for any application, website, or other services that are not controlled by Meta.
If Meta Platforms Data includes user passwords that Company Processes on Meta’s behalf, then Company shall encrypt in storage and transit such user passwords.
If Meta Platforms Data includes In-Scope Security Telephone Numbers, then Company shall not Process such In-Scope Security Telephone Numbers for the purpose of serving advertisements.
3.2
Data Incidents.
To the extent Company receives or Processes Meta Platforms Data:
If Company suffers a Data Incident, Company shall provide notice to Meta at
vendor-incident@meta.com
without undue delay following Company’s discovery thereof.
In the event of any such Data Incident, Company shall begin remediation of the Data Incident without undue delay and reasonably cooperate with Meta, including by informing Meta in reasonable detail of the impact of the Data Incident upon Meta Platforms Data and the corrective actions being taken, and keeping Meta updated about Company’s compliance with any notification or other Data Protection Requirements applicable to the Processing of Meta Platforms Data.
To the extent the Agreement specifies Company as a “Service Provider” or “Processor," Company shall further:
Provide to Meta the notice in Section 3.2(a) without undue delay and, in any event, within the earlier of forty-eight (48) hours or in accordance with the Data Protection Requirements applicable to Meta Platforms Data; and
Provide to Meta: (A) any and all reasonable information in Company’s possession or control relating to a Data Incident; (B) such assistance as Meta reasonably requires to enable Meta to investigate such Data Incident and discharge its obligations under Data Protection Requirements applicable to Meta Platforms Data or the Processing thereof (including all information reasonably required to notify any supervisory authority or other relevant regulator, individual and/or other third party); and (C) any other resources and assistance as reasonably required by Meta in connection with such notification(s), as applicable.
General
4.1
Survival.
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in the Agreement, Company’s obligations regarding Meta Platforms Data or Personal Data will survive any termination or expiration of the Agreement to the extent Company continues to retain or otherwise Process Meta Platforms Data or Personal Data (as such retention or other Processing may be permitted under the Agreement or Applicable Law).
4.2
Severability & Waiver.
If any portion of this DPA is found to be unenforceable, then that portion will be limited to the minimum extent necessary to remain enforceable or, if necessary, severed and the remaining portions will remain in full force and effect. Any delay or failure by Meta to enforce any of its rights under this DPA will not be deemed a waiver.
4.3
Amendment.
Meta may need to update this DPA from time to time, including to accurately reflect or comply with Applicable Law. Such update shall be effective on the Last Updated date. Meta shall use commercially reasonable efforts to provide at least thirty (30) days’ prior notice to Company of any material updates to this DPA. By Processing Personal Data under the Agreement, Company agrees to review and comply with the latest version of this DPA, and Company waives any objection to the means and manner of Company’s acceptance of this DPA that may be specified in or required by the Agreement.
Definitions
5.1
Definitions.
For purposes of this DPA, the following terms shall have the meanings set out below:
“Affiliate”
means, with respect to a Party, an entity which, directly or indirectly, owns or controls, is owned or is controlled by, or is under common ownership or control of a Party. As used in this term, “control” means the power to direct the management or affairs of an entity, and “ownership” means the beneficial ownership of fifty percent (50%) (or, if the applicable jurisdiction does not allow majority ownership, the maximum amount permitted under such law) or more of the voting equity securities or other equivalent voting interests of the entity.
“Agreement”
means each agreement, contract, or written instrument (including any Master Subscription Agreement, Professional Services Agreement, Consulting Agreement, Master Event Sponsorship Agreement, Master Services Agreement, Engagement Letter, Statement of Work, Order Form, Exhibit, Event Exhibit, Amendment, Addendum, or other Attachment) that Company enters into with Meta that incorporates by reference this DPA, including any other terms (including data protection addendums) incorporated into such document.
“APAC Data Protection Requirements”
means any and all Applicable Law related to data protection, data security, marketing, privacy, or the Processing of Personal Data in the countries in Asia (excluding the countries in the Middle East) and the countries that border the Pacific Ocean on the Asian side (including Australia, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, New Zealand, Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Taiwan, Thailand, and Vietnam).
“Applicable Law”
means any applicable law, regulation, directive, or other binding requirements (each as may be implemented, amended, extended, superseded, or re-enacted from time to time), including but not limited to, for the avoidance of doubt, Data Protection Requirements.
“Company”
means the entity that entered into the Agreement with Meta, and such entity’s Affiliates to the extent they Process Meta Platforms Data under the Agreement.
“Controller”
and
“Third Party”
(or equivalent terms) means their respective definitions under Data Protection Requirements.
“Data Incident”
means: (i) the loss or deletion, or unlawful, accidental or unauthorized Processing of any Meta Platforms Data; (ii) any breach or compromise of the security, confidentiality, privacy, availability or integrity of any Meta Platforms Data or information systems that store or otherwise Process Meta Platforms Data; or (iii) any other incident involving Meta Platforms Data that may constitute a Personal Data breach, security incident, or similar term under Data Protection Requirements.
“Data Protection Requirements”
means, to the extent applicable: (i) APAC Data Protection Requirements; (ii) European Data Protection Requirements; (iii) LATAM, AMET, and Canadian Data Protection Requirements; (iv) USA Data Protection Requirements; (v) mandatory industry rules and standards including, to the extent applicable, the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (“
PCI-DSS
”); and (vi) any and all other Applicable Law related to data protection, data security, marketing, privacy, or the Processing of Personal Data.
“European Data Protection Requirements”
means any and all Applicable Law related to data protection, data security, marketing, privacy, or the Processing of Personal Data in the European Union (“
EU
”), the European Economic Area (“
EEA
”), Switzerland, or United Kingdom (“
UK
”), including, to the extent applicable, the Regulation (EU) 2016/679 (“
